    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-09-17T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-09-17T13:00:00-05:00" n="278"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d278">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94 Commission/359: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul at Geneva (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_VSRG1" type="to"
                            >Gilbert</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-09-17T14:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 17, 1932—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>123. Your political despatch 331, August 31, page 2, first paragraph.<note n="67"
                        xml:id="d278fn67">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_216">p. 216</ref>, paragraph
                        beginning “The speech is considered first …”</note>
                </p>
                <p>1. The Secretary and <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_MMGFR1">General
                        McCoy</persName> have had no correspondence on this subject and <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_MMGFR1">General McCoy</persName> has made no report
                    to the Department. We have regarded <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_MMGFR1"
                        >General McCoy</persName>, in his capacity as a member of the Commission, as
                    in no way a representative or agent of the American Government. Such meager
                    knowledge as we have of the probable contents of the Commission’s report has
                    been gained fragmentarily from various sources. A news story which appeared in
                    the <hi rend="italic">Baltimore Sun</hi> some weeks ago beginning with a
                    statement to the effect that officials here had received a “preliminary report”
                    was a fabrication.</p>
                <p>Without taking the initiative, you may discreetly make use of the above in
                    conversations with responsible inquirers.</p>
                <p>2. Send London a copy of your despatch under reference and of this telegram.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_SHL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
